        "content": {
          "Prompt": {
            "prompt": "Why does my gh auth not last in the session?"
          }
        },
        "timestamp": "2025-12-03T17:00:19.794071663+01:00",
        "images": null
      },
      "assistant": {
        "Response": {
          "message_id": "b572cc88-f91c-460c-b342-a50a0b598f33",
          "content": "Each tool execution I run is in a **separate shell process** - they don't share environment or authentication state.\n\nWhen you run `gh auth login` in your terminal, it:\n1. Stores credentials in `~/.config/gh/hosts.yml`\n2. Sets up git credential helper\n\nBut when I execute commands via `execute_bash`, each invocation is a fresh shell that:\n- Doesn't inherit your interactive session's environment\n- May not load the same shell config files\n- Runs as a subprocess with isolated state\n\n**Why git push might not work for me:**\n- SSH keys might require an agent that's only running in your session\n- Git credential helper might need interactive prompts\n- Environment variables (like `GH_TOKEN`) aren't inherited\n\nThat's why you need to run git push commands yourself in your authenticated terminal session."
        }
      },
      "request_metadata": {
        "request_id": "ff758ea2-6c9a-41a4-9ed7-3e9213f06ced",
