  "transcript": [
    "> This current directory is a ruby project to implement the mqtt protocol. I want to set it up for use with you.",
    "I'll help you set up this MQTT Ruby project for working together. Let me first check the current structure to understand what's already in place.\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "Good! I can see you already have `.amazonq/rules/` directory with some rules. The project is well-structured with multiple gems. Let me check what rules you currently have:\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "Perfect! You already have good rules in place. Let me check the Ruby version and verify the setup:\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "Great! Your project is already well-configured for AI assistance. Here's what you have:\n\n**Current Setup:**\n- ✅ `.amazonq/rules/` directory with codebase conventions\n- ✅ Ruby 3.4.1 via RVM\n- ✅ Multi-gem structure (mqtt-core, mqtt-v3, mqtt-v5, concurrent_monitor)\n- ✅ Test suite with minitest\n- ✅ Documentation (README, YARD)\n\n**What I understand about your project:**\n- Pure Ruby MQTT protocol implementation (v3.1.1 and v5.0)\n- Supports both threaded and async (fiber-based) clients\n- QoS 0/1/2 with session management\n- Follows gem boundaries strictly (no `require_relative` across gems)\n\n**I'm ready to help you with:**\n- Writing/debugging code across the gem structure\n- Running tests using RVM and bundle exec\n- Following your documentation-as-truth principle\n- Respecting gem boundaries\n- Working with both sync and async implementations\n\nIs there anything specific you'd like to work on, or would you like me to add any additional rules or documentation to help our collaboration?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> Explain the approach to github actions and releasing this multi-gem project (note that I have never run this yet)",
    "Let me check your GitHub Actions configuration to understand the release approach:\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "## Release Approach for Multi-Gem Project\n\nYour project has a **coordinated multi-gem release strategy** that hasn't been executed yet. Here's how it works:\n\n### **Gem Structure & Dependencies**\n```\nconcurrent_monitor (no deps)\n    ↓\nmqtt-core (depends on concurrent_monitor)\n    ↓\nmqtt-v3, mqtt-v5 (both depend on mqtt-core)\n```\n\n### **Version Management**\n- All gems share the **same version number** (currently `0.0.1`)\n- Versions are kept in sync via `VERSION_FILES` in Rakefile\n- `GemHelper` generates version suffixes based on git context:\n  - **main branch**: `0.0.1` (clean version)\n  - **feature branch**: `0.0.1.feature.branch.name`\n  - **tag `v0.0.1`**: `0.0.1`\n  - **pre-release tag**: `0.0.1.branch.name`\n\n### **Release Workflow (Never Run Yet)**\n\n**1. Bump version** (on main branch):\n```bash\nrake version:bump_minor  # Updates both version.rb files\ngit commit -am 'Bump version to 0.1.0'\ngit push\n```\n\n**2. Create release tag**:\n```bash\nrake version:tag  # Creates v0.1.0 tag (main branch only)\ngit push --tags\n```\n\n**3. GitHub Actions triggers** (on tag push):\n- `release.yml` workflow runs\n- Builds gems in dependency order\n- Pushes to RubyGems using `RUBYGEMS_API_KEY` secret\n\n**For pre-releases** (from feature branches):\n```bash\nrake version:tag_prerelease  # Creates v0.0.1.feature.name\ngit push --tags\n```\n\n### **GitHub Actions Workflows**\n\n- **`build.yml`**: Runs on every push/PR - tests with mosquitto broker\n- **`version-check.yml`**: Validates version bumps in PRs\n- **`pre-release.yml`**: Manual workflow to test gem building\n- **`release.yml`**: Triggered by version tags - publishes to RubyGems\n\n### **Before First Release**\nYou need to:\n1. Set `RUBYGEMS_API_KEY` secret in GitHub repo settings\n2. Create \"release\" environment in GitHub (referenced in release.yml)\n3. Verify all gems build: `rake gems:build`\n4. Test release workflow with pre-release tag first\n\n### **Key Safety Features**\n- Versions must match across gems (enforced)\n- Working directory must be clean (enforced)\n- Release tags only from main branch (enforced)\n- Gems released in dependency order (hardcoded in workflow)\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> OK what do we need to do to do a test using the prerelease structure.",
    "Let me check your current git status and then outline the steps:\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "> y",
    "You have uncommitted changes on main. Here's what to do for a pre-release test:\n\n## Steps for Pre-Release Test\n\n**1. Commit your current work** (you're on main with changes):\n```bash\ncd /home/ggardner/workspace-ruby/async-mqtt\ngit add -A\ngit commit -m \"Add release workflows and version management\"\ngit push\n```\n\n**2. Create a test branch**:\n```bash\ngit checkout -b test-release\n```\n\n**3. Verify versions are in sync**:\n```bash\nrake version:show\n```\n\n**4. Create pre-release tag** (from test-release branch):\n```bash\nrake version:tag_prerelease\n```\nThis will create tag like `v0.0.1.test.release`\n\n**5. Push the tag**:\n```bash\ngit push origin v0.0.1.test.release\n```\n\n**6. Manually trigger pre-release check** (GitHub UI):\n- Go to Actions → \"Pre-release Check\"\n- Click \"Run workflow\"\n- Select branch: `test-release`\n- Input gems: `all`\n- Click \"Run workflow\"\n\nThis will build all gems and show their contents without publishing.\n\n**7. If successful, test the release workflow**:\n```bash\n# Trigger release.yml manually from GitHub Actions UI\n# Or just verify gems built locally:\nrake gems:build\nls -la gems/*/pkg/*.gem\n```\n\nWant me to run the first few steps for you?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> Should we use a different branch?",
    "Yes, good thinking. Since you're on `main` with uncommitted changes that add the release infrastructure itself, you should:\n\n**Option 1: Commit to main first** (recommended)\n```bash\ngit checkout -b release-infrastructure\ngit add -A\ngit commit -m \"Add release workflows and version management\"\ngit push -u origin release-infrastructure\n# Create PR, merge to main\n# Then create test-release branch from main\n```\n\n**Option 2: Create feature branch now**\n```bash\ngit checkout -b release-infrastructure\ngit add -A\ngit commit -m \"Add release workflows and version management\"\ngit push -u origin release-infrastructure\n# Test pre-release from this branch\nrake version:tag_prerelease  # Creates v0.0.1.release.infrastructure\n```\n\n**Option 1 is cleaner** because:\n- Gets release infrastructure into main first\n- Then test pre-release from a separate throwaway branch\n- Keeps the test isolated from the infrastructure changes\n\nWhich approach do you prefer?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> maybe I should have a naming standard but release-infrastructure is too long.",
    "Good point. Common Ruby/Rails conventions:\n\n**Short and clear options:**\n- `release-setup`\n- `gem-release`\n- `ci-release`\n- `release-ci`\n\n**My recommendation:** `release-setup`\n\nIt's clear, short, and describes what it does. Want to use that?\n\n```bash\ngit checkout -b release-setup\n```\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> I like ci as a prefix. actually remind me what tags conventional commits use for change log messages relating to non user fixes, ci etc ?",
    "Conventional Commits types:\n\n**User-facing:**\n- `feat:` - New features (shows in changelog)\n- `fix:` - Bug fixes (shows in changelog)\n- `perf:` - Performance improvements (shows in changelog)\n\n**Non-user-facing (typically hidden from changelog):**\n- `ci:` - CI/CD changes (workflows, actions)\n- `build:` - Build system changes (dependencies, scripts)\n- `chore:` - Maintenance tasks (no production code change)\n- `docs:` - Documentation only\n- `style:` - Code style/formatting (no logic change)\n- `refactor:` - Code restructuring (no behavior change)\n- `test:` - Test additions/changes\n\nFor your release workflows, use:\n- **Branch:** `ci-release` or `ci/release`\n- **Commit:** `ci: add release workflows and version management`\n\nWant to go with `ci-release` or `ci/release`?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> Ah, 'chore' was what I was thinking.  But ci is good.  Sometimes I use dates for branch names eg ci-nov25.",
    "Date-based branch names are practical for tracking when work happened. For today:\n\n```bash\ngit checkout -b ci-dec03\ngit add -A\ngit commit -m \"ci: add release workflows and version management\"\ngit push -u origin ci-dec03\n```\n\nWant me to run these commands for you?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> Oh I meant month/year (and yes I forgot we were in december already).  ci/release'",
    "Got it - `ci/release` it is:\n\n```bash\ngit checkout -b ci/release\ngit add -A\ngit commit -m \"ci: add release workflows and version management\"\ngit push -u origin ci/release\n```\n\nWant me to run these?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> Before we do that, will the '/' get appropriately translated in our pre-release gem version (not sure / is valid)",
    "Good catch! Let me check the `GemHelper`:\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "Yes! Line 32 shows: `.tr('/_-', '.')` \n\nThis translates `/`, `_`, and `-` to `.`\n\nSo `ci/release` becomes `0.0.1.ci.release` ✓\n\nThe `/` is valid for branch names and will be properly converted for gem versions. Go ahead with `ci/release`.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> Before we commit it.  Run your eye over the git hub action code, rakefile, gemspecs etc to check for bugs in this process.",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "> y",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "## Issues Found:\n\n**🔴 CRITICAL: Version file mismatch**\n\nYour `VERSION_FILES` in Rakefile only tracks 2 files:\n```ruby\nVERSION_FILES = %w[\n  gems/mqtt-core/lib/mqtt/version.rb\n  gems/concurrent_monitor/lib/concurrent_monitor/version.rb\n]\n```\n\nBut you have **4 version files** that need to stay in sync:\n- `gems/mqtt-core/lib/mqtt/version.rb` ✓\n- `gems/concurrent_monitor/lib/concurrent_monitor/version.rb` ✓\n- `gems/mqtt-v3/lib/mqtt/v3/version.rb` ❌ (missing)\n- `gems/mqtt-v5/lib/mqtt/v5/version.rb` ❌ (missing)\n\n**🟡 ISSUE: Gemspec paths**\n\n`mqtt-v3` and `mqtt-v5` gemspecs load version from:\n```ruby\nrequire_relative '../mqtt-core/lib/mqtt/version'  # MQTT::VERSION\n```\n\nBut they have their own version files with `MQTT::V3::VERSION` and `MQTT::V5::VERSION`.\n\n**Fix needed:**\n\nEither:\n1. **Use shared version** (simpler) - mqtt-v3/v5 use `MQTT::VERSION` from mqtt-core\n2. **Track all versions** - add v3/v5 version files to `VERSION_FILES` and update gemspecs\n\nWhich approach do you want? I recommend **option 1** (shared version) since they're released together.\n[Tool uses: none]",
