    "> y",
    "The branch exists locally but hasn't been pushed yet (no `[origin/ci/release]` shown). You just need:\n\n```bash\ngit push -u origin ci/release\n```\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> what is the -u ?",
    "`-u` is short for `--set-upstream`\n\nIt sets the remote branch as the upstream tracking branch for your local branch. This means:\n\n**With `-u` (first time):**\n```bash\ngit push -u origin ci/release\n```\n- Pushes the branch\n- Sets `origin/ci/release` as the upstream\n- Future pushes can just use `git push` (no need to specify remote/branch)\n\n**Without `-u`:**\n```bash\ngit push origin ci/release\n```\n- Pushes the branch\n- But doesn't set tracking\n- Future pushes need `git push origin ci/release` every time\n\nUse `-u` the first time you push a new branch, then just `git push` after that.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> OK that's done.  What is our next step to test?",
    "Now test the pre-release workflow:\n\n**1. Create pre-release tag:**\n```bash\ncd /home/ggardner/workspace-ruby/async-mqtt\nrake version:tag_prerelease\n```\nThis creates tag `v0.0.1.ci.release`\n\n**2. Push the tag:**\n```bash\ngit push --tags\n```\n\n**3. Check GitHub Actions:**\n- Go to your repo → Actions tab\n- Should see \"Release Gems\" workflow triggered by the tag\n- It will try to build and push gems (will fail without `RUBYGEMS_API_KEY` secret)\n\n**4. Or manually test pre-release check:**\n- Go to Actions → \"Pre-release Check\" \n- Click \"Run workflow\"\n- Branch: `ci/release`\n- Gems: `all`\n- This just builds and shows gem contents (doesn't publish)\n\nWhich do you want to try first? I'd suggest **option 4** (manual pre-release check) since it won't try to publish.\n[Tool uses: none]",
