    "Understood. Here are the commands for you to run:\n\n```bash\ncd /home/ggardner/workspace-ruby/async-mqtt\ngit add -A\ngit commit -m \"ci: update rubocop config and fix style issues\"\ngit push\n```\n\nThis will commit:\n- Updated `.rubocop.yml` (plugins syntax)\n- Auto-corrected style issues\n- Inline `rubocop:disable` comments for the predicate method false positives\n- Updated `Gemfile.lock` (from bundle update)\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> Why does my gh auth not last in the session?",
    "Each tool execution I run is in a **separate shell process** - they don't share environment or authentication state.\n\nWhen you run `gh auth login` in your terminal, it:\n1. Stores credentials in `~/.config/gh/hosts.yml`\n2. Sets up git credential helper\n\nBut when I execute commands via `execute_bash`, each invocation is a fresh shell that:\n- Doesn't inherit your interactive session's environment\n- May not load the same shell config files\n- Runs as a subprocess with isolated state\n\n**Why git push might not work for me:**\n- SSH keys might require an agent that's only running in your session\n- Git credential helper might need interactive prompts\n- Environment variables (like `GH_TOKEN`) aren't inherited\n\nThat's why you need to run git push commands yourself in your authenticated terminal session.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> I did this> \nOpening in existing browser session.> \n✓ Authentication complete.> \n- gh config set -h github.com git_protocol https> \n✓ Configured git protocol> \n✓ Logged in as lwoggardner> \n! You were already logged in to this account> \n",
    "That's `gh` CLI authentication, which is separate from git push authentication.\n\nFor git push over HTTPS, you need a credential helper. Try:\n\n```bash\ngit config --global credential.helper store\n```\n\nThen the next time you push, it will prompt for credentials once and store them.\n\nOr use SSH instead:\n```bash\ngit remote set-url origin git@github.com:lwoggardner/ruby-mqtt-gems.git\n```\n\nThen git push will use your SSH key (if you have one set up with GitHub).\n\nWhat does `git remote -v` show?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> ggardner@spix:~/workspace-ruby/async-mqtt$ git remote -v> \norigin\thttps://github.com/lwoggardner/ruby-mqtt-gems.git (fetch)> \norigin\thttps://github.com/lwoggardner/ruby-mqtt-gems.git (push)",
    "You're using HTTPS. The `gh` auth should work as a credential helper. Check if it's configured:\n\n```bash\ngit config --global credential.helper\n```\n\nIf it doesn't show `gh`, set it:\n\n```bash\ngh auth setup-git\n```\n\nThis configures git to use `gh` as the credential helper for GitHub. Then `git push` should work.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> ggardner@spix:~/workspace-ruby/async-mqtt$ git config --global credential.helper> \ncache> \n",
    "It's using `cache` which stores credentials in memory temporarily. Run:\n\n```bash\ngh auth setup-git\n```\n\nThis will configure git to use `gh` as the credential helper, so your `gh auth login` will work for git operations.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> ggardner@spix:~/workspace-ruby/async-mqtt$ gh auth setup-git> \nggardner@spix:~/workspace-ruby/async-mqtt$ git config --global credential.helper> \ncache> \n",
    "Interesting - `gh auth setup-git` didn't change it. Check the full credential config:\n\n```bash\ngit config --global --get-regexp credential\n```\n\nThe `gh` credential helper might be configured per-host rather than globally. Try pushing now - it should work since you just ran `gh auth login`.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> > \ncredential.helper cache> \ncredential.https://github.com.helper > \ncredential.https://github.com.helper !/usr/bin/gh auth git-credential> \ncredential.https://gist.github.com.helper > \ncredential.https://gist.github.com.helper !/usr/bin/gh auth git-credential> \n",
    "Perfect! You have `gh auth git-credential` configured for `github.com`. The `cache` helper runs first, then falls back to `gh`.\n\nYour git push should work now. Try it:\n\n```bash\ngit push\n```\n[Tool uses: none]",
